ROOT CAUSE: `src/be_parser.c:706-716` (`index_expr`) and `src/be_parser.c:689-704` (`member_expr`). When the receiver `e` is already an `ETMEMBER`/`ETINDEX` suffix expression (e.g. `c.l` in `c.l[0..1]` or `c.l[t_i]`), the parser does NOT materialize/cache it before evaluating the inner expression. The inner `expr(parser, &e1)` may emit instructions (e.g. `OP_RANGE` for `0..1`, or `OP_GETGBL` for `t_i`) that allocate temporary registers and overwrite registers that the pending `OP_GETMBR`/`OP_GETIDX` for the receiver still depends on. Then `be_code_index` / `package_suffix` reads stale `ss.obj`/`ss.idx` slots, so the resulting `GETIDX` is applied to wrong values — that is why `t_101_nok_1()` (range slice on `c.l`) and `t_101_nok_2()` (variable index on `c.l`) return wrong values, while the `_ok_` versions (where the receiver is first stored in a fresh local `l2`) work. Test fails at `tests/suffix.be:25`.

LOCAL FIX: In `index_expr` (be_parser.c:706) and `member_expr` (be_parser.c:689), call `suffix_alloc_reg(parser, e)` (or inline its body) right after `check_var(parser, e)` and before parsing the inner expression — i.e. when `e->type` is already `ETMEMBER`/`ETINDEX`, eagerly emit code to load the receiver to a fresh register and freeze that register, so subsequent `expr()` calls cannot clobber it. Concretely, before `scan_next_token` skipping `[` / `.`, do:
```c
if (e->type == ETMEMBER || e->type == ETINDEX) {
    suffix_alloc_reg(parser, e);
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: The class of bug is "deferred suffix expressions whose live registers are not protected from intervening codegen." Make register-protection a property of `bexpdesc` rather than something each call site remembers to re-do. Two structural options: (a) have `be_code_member`/`be_code_index` immediately reify the receiver into a stable register (i.e. always `exp2anyreg` the object before storing into `ss.obj`, marking that slot as locked in `finfo->freereg`), so any later `expr()` call automatically allocates above it; or (b) introduce a `with_protected_regs(finfo, e, body)` helper used by every parser routine that calls `expr()` while holding a partially-built suffix (`compound_assign` already does this manually — generalize it). Either change eliminates the whole family of "evaluating an inner expression clobbers an in-flight ETMEMBER/ETINDEX receiver" bugs (issue #101 and friends) instead of patching them site-by-site.
